message.text:
		@G[c3 stills_140.png]@L
		@H Historical Background @L
		The Roman city of Valentia Edetanorum was founded in 138 BC on the coast of the Balearic Sea in the province of Hispania. The name originates from the Latin word meaning "strength" or "valor", likely due to the Roman practice of recognizing the valor of former Roman soldiers after a war. The Roman historian Livy explains that the founding of Valentia in the 2nd century BC was due to the settling of the Roman soldiers who fought against the Lusitanian rebel Viriathus. @L@L
		Many Roman cities were founded by settling veteran soldiers with their families. The success of this practice varied, as soldiers who were campaigning for 25 years would often know little about agriculture. @L@L
		A Roman cultural belief was that every good politician would make an excellent general and vice versa. Similarly, they believed that every farmer would make a good soldier, and thus every soldier would make a good farmer. @L@L
		Since there are no other major topics, let us cover the Roman triumph. A triumph was the highest military achievement a politician could attain and usually lead to a future political career, since during a triumph the armies and general would be invited by the Senate to Rome itself where they would parade in the streets and share the spoils of war, organize games, and show propaganda paintings. The biggest achievement would be to show and execute a monarch of the conquered peoples in one's triumphal procession, which is what happened to Vercingetorix during Caesar's eventual Gallic War triumph. @L@L
		To be eligible to receive a triumph, there were two major requirements: a general had to successfully annex new territory for Rome and had to be acclaimed "imperator" by his own troops. Imperator can be understood as "one who commands" and would be a title reserved for generals who cultivated strong esprit de corps and were successful. @L@L
		The Roman triumph was a celebration of achievements and thus, a form of rewarding merit amongst its leaders. Unfortunately, during the Late Republic even the act of awarding triumph was highjacked by factionalism and later during the Roman Empire, merit would be swept aside completely by rewarding people with familial ties to the emperor to centralize power. @L@L
		This was one of the many reasons for the Roman Empire's eventual decline, as favoritism and cults of personality would erode and weaken institutions and see competence as a threat to the established order. Instead of granting competent generals a triumph, emperors would see them as rivals and threats. @L@L

