		@H Instructions @L
        Governor, the Republic is now in need of a colony on the coast of the Balearic Sea. The area chosen has plentiful local resources and fertile lands elevated on hillsides above the future city level. Most people will live on the hills surrounding the coastal center of trade. @L@L
		As regards matters of commerce, many other cities in the region already have thriving industry and are not requesting manufactured goods. As such, your economy will need to rely on the bulk export of raw materials. You must wisely place your docks and warehouses to minimize transit delays; highways and even a lighthouse are also recommended, despite their high construction costs. @L@L
		As the province is sparsely populated, your entertainment options will be limited until at least some patricians settle in Valentia. As you are far from the Roman heartland, corruption is expected to be a potential issue; monitor your city's treasury carefully to detect any accounting anomalies. @L@L
		Rome is not currently involved in any large-scale conflicts in the area, so Valentia is in a safer position than many other cities in the Republic. However, the local Iberians are still a threat and may attack the city on more than one occasion. You will require a garrison of troops to ensure that peace reigns in Valentia. @L@L
		Keep in mind that I will ask you to achieve levels of prosperity that have been unparalleled in your cities thus far. Good luck governor. @L@L

